WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Brandon Farr, Co-Founder & CEO, Quantitative Research, Quantitative Finance

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Start right in with it by introducing Brandon Farr from Copper Rock Capital Partners.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Thank you.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Please welcome Brandon Farr.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:27.000
Good afternoon and welcome.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:32.000
My name is Brandon Farr. I'm the lead quantitative researcher at Copper Rock Capital Partners.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:39.000
We are a Boston-based long-only equity firm serving the institutional marketplace.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:45.000
We have clients from around the world with two-thirds of the money we manage coming from outside the United States.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:51.000
I started using R in 2005 because it was the most powerful analytical tool I'd ever come across.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.000
Each year, R has become more powerful.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Fifteen years ago, R use in finance was rare.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:04.000
It's become more common, but what has been the impact?

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
Let's take a look at this quote from Alliance Bernstein.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:18.000
We estimate that at least 99% of so-called fundamental models for individual companies manifest themselves in Excel.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:24.000
So our industry is still relying on a tool built for the data challenges of the 20th century.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000
People use Excel because it's easy to learn.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
But as we all know, it then takes on a life of its own.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:37.000
Ad hoc solutions end up becoming the basis for important decisions.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:43.000
But better data analysis requires reproducibility and scalability.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:49.000
So in preparing for today, I decided to focus on what makes R compelling for those cases.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:54.000
What's going to dent that 99%?

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.000
I'm going to focus on two important use cases.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:01.000
First, using R to do better analysis.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:09.000
By better analysis, I mean you spend more time interpreting your data than manipulating it.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:15.000
Second, using R to build what you cannot buy in the marketplace.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:20.000
I'll use Shiny to make my case.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:21.000
We start with data.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Good analysis is based on sound data.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:29.000
Financial World has many providers supplying data to help us understand companies and markets.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:35.000
Bloomberg and FactSet are a couple of the providers that I frequently use.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.000
Here's Apple's price chart in the Bloomberg terminal.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:45.000
In the terminal, I can change the time period, data frequency, and overlay calculations onto this chart.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:47.000
This is great, but it doesn't scale.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.000
How do I look at 10 stocks?

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:54.000
How do I look at a portfolio of stocks?

00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:01.000
To do scalable analysis, I usually need to report or analyze what I'll call reported data.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:07.000
Mine typically comes from FactSet and is formatted for printing, not for processing.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:09.000
You can see the header is messy.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.000
Dates are formatted as text.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Rows are grouped together.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:19.000
But R allows us to do good data analysis even when we start with messy data.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:23.000
Let's look at a typical scenario.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:27.000
As an investment team, we need to know what is driving markets.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:31.000
Here's data from the fourth quarter of last year.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:35.000
These are sector performance reports for the U.S. and global markets.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:40.000
In the spreadsheet I get from FactSet, this data comes separated into tabs,

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:46.000
and the stock data is grouped by sector and hidden because everything has been collapsed.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:51.000
Now, tables of data are useful, but visualizations are better.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:58.000
With a chart, we can quickly see that healthcare and technology drove both the U.S. and world markets in the fourth quarter.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:04.000
This is hard to pull from tabular data, especially if it's on separate tabs.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
So how would we visualize this in Excel?

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:11.000
Well, I would do something like this.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:19.000
I'd gather the data into a single tab, making sure everything's aligned so that if I'm labeling data, the labels are appropriately placed.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:23.000
I'd create a plot referencing the group totals.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
And then I'd customize the plot.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:33.000
I'm sure most of you have done something similar to this and are aware that pitfalls lie ahead.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:38.000
It's my experience that anything that's useful leads to further questions.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Is our Excel process up to the task of answering further questions?

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
Okay, fine, but what worked in the emerging markets?

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:53.000
Did healthcare and technology lead in the fourth quarter of 2018 as well?

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:58.000
How do we answer these questions with our Excel process?

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:05.000
Well, I'll argue that just one additional tab of data is going to require me to rework my entire process.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:10.000
If I need to turn this around quickly, which I often do, I can only hope that I'll be accurate.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:14.000
To ensure that I'm accurate, I probably need to start over.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.000
The Excel solution just feels fragile.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:29.000
My sense is that even if you are very good at plumbing in Excel, extending an established process is burdensome, fraught with error, and probably requires a lot of repetition.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:33.000
This is a major hurdle to doing better data analysis.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:38.000
So how does R help us do this analysis in a better way?

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:44.000
Well, in R, I'm going to complete the same steps, but I'm going to do it in a structured way with code.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:49.000
I'll specify the data file. I will read and prepare the market data.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:54.000
I will collect the group information, and then I'll plot those groups.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:58.000
R allows us to break a process into logical, distinct steps.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:03.000
With proper naming, the logic of the process is explicit and readable.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:08.000
With care, when we need to extend this process, nothing needs to change.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
Let me walk through the code.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:17.000
Let's take a minute to look at how easy setting up robust processes has become in R.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:24.000
This is important because we are trying to convince ourselves and others to do the same sort of analysis in R, do more of it.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
Remember, we're trying to put a dent in that 99%.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:31.000
This is the heart of our process here.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:41.000
Here we see good examples of names indicating function and logical separation of tasks.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:44.000
Let's look at the function prepareMarketData.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:49.000
Our function reads the tab names from the file and puts them into a tbl.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:55.000
Next, we make calls to read grouped data with the help of mutate and map.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:01.000
After this step, we have a tbl with two rows representing the two markets in our analysis,

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:05.000
with all of the underlying data conveniently stored in list columns.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:14.000
This is a very powerful structure and an example of something that wasn't possible 15 years ago, even in R.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:20.000
But how did regroup data handle all of the messiness of our data?

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.000
Though reported data is often messy, it is usually consistent.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:33.000
By taking advantage of the patterns we observe in the spreadsheet file, we can systematically handle the collapsed data.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:41.000
Here we see sector and company names occupy separate columns in the spreadsheet, plus the sector group row stands on its own.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:44.000
Healthcare, shown here, is not carried down the column.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:49.000
So in this representation, healthcare or group membership is implied.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:53.000
With R, we make it explicit.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:59.000
This is a good example of how clear it is in code when we are manipulating data.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
All we need to look for, in this case, is mutate commands.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:09.000
Copy and paste manipulation is documented nowhere.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:20.000
Additionally, a function like this is a perfect candidate for a package, so it can be reused across many analyses.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:28.000
Collect groups is just a simple function that unnests the list columns and then filters to just give me the group total rows.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
If you guys haven't seen this pattern, it's one that's very powerful.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:41.000
Note that we will maintain the natural relationships between the market names and the underlying market data automatically.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:47.000
Finally, we pipe to a plotting function that captures all of our logic.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:58.000
So, we have encapsulated the entirety of our data process into four functions, none more than seven or eight lines long, and all very readable.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.000
This is better analysis with R.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:03.000
We get reliability.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:10.000
Our process is replicable and efficient because we aren't copying and pasting.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:16.000
Errors or future changes can be traced to the impacted steps and corrected or implemented.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:24.000
In my experience, processes set up in this way typically fail not because of coding problems, but because of data changes.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
A quick aside.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:32.000
Last week, I was asked the specifics of how I performed a what-if analysis on some of our historic portfolio holdings.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:41.000
It had been months since I had done the work, and yet within two minutes of reviewing the code, I was able to answer the question accurately and confidently.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:48.000
If I had done the work in Excel, I would have had no chance.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:55.000
Next, I'd like to show you how we have used R and Shiny at Copper Rock to build something we couldn't buy.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
Our quantitative model covers over 10,000 stocks.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:05.000
In the past, we delivered this to analysts and portfolio managers in an Excel spreadsheet.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:09.000
Here's an example of one of the weekly files.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.000
It only contains the most recent data.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
It's frustrating to filter.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:17.000
When you apply filters in Excel, you can't understand the logic.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:22.000
The best you can tell is whether or not a column has a filter applied to it or not.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:33.000
It's difficult to see the relationship between groups of stocks, and it's difficult to integrate this data with other data from our vendors.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
So we created Cognos.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:40.000
Cognos is a Shiny app built to meet our team's specific analytical needs.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:44.000
Nothing available from Bloomberg or FactSet matches it.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:51.000
Even though we are a small, focused shop, R and Shiny has allowed us to create this powerful custom application.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:55.000
Let's take a closer look.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:59.000
Here's a snapshot of Microsoft through the lens of our quantitative model.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:06.000
Our model data indicated here comes from a Microsoft Azure database.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:17.000
We pull in data from Bloomberg via their API, and MSCI ESG data is sourced from flat files.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:22.000
All of this data provides the context that was missing from our Excel-based solution.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:25.000
Data is no longer siloed.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
Analysts don't have to make the connection.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:30.000
Cognos is doing it for them.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:37.000
Just seeing the data in the middle of the screen moved our conversations from conjecture to data-based reality.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:43.000
We no longer had to rely on the recollection that, oh, the model has always liked Microsoft.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:50.000
Cognos can tell us, and the orange line tells us it hasn't always liked Microsoft.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:56.000
On this screen, you see two important components of our quantitative model represented in the scattered plot.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:00.000
Higher scores should indicate better stocks.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:06.000
We've found it most productive to reserve our fundamental research for highly ranked stocks.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:13.000
So by focusing on stocks in the first quadrant, analysts can better allocate their research time.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:19.000
With the interactivity of Shiny apps, our analysts quickly navigate their way through a massive universe.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:22.000
Cognos really helps them kick-start their analysis.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:27.000
It is used by our team all day long.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:30.000
R and Shiny helped us build something we couldn't buy.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:33.000
Cognos has become our hub for data delivery.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:42.000
It is naturally extensible, needs no training, and requires very few IT resources.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:50.000
So we walked through an example of how easy it is to set up a process to do better analysis in R.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:13:00.000
Then we looked at how Shiny apps can help you build something you can't buy, matched to exactly the way your team works.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:07.000
I think it is a great example of how a relatively simple Shiny app can have a significant impact.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:12.000
Recall, my focus for today was to make a dent in the 99%.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
I think these two use cases are examples of how we might start.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
I encourage you all to chip in.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:25.000
Thank you very much for your time and attention.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.000
I'm happy to take any questions.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
Thank you.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
Thank you, Brandon.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:44.000
Just a reminder that you can ask questions on Slido.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:48.000
A couple of questions from William Hsu.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.000
Data table is multi-threaded and very fast.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:54.000
What are the performance metrics between Arrow and data table?

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.000
Oh, sorry.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
I got the wrong room.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
Come on, man.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.000
I've got one for you.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
What package, new package, are you most excited about?

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:18.000
Well, as I said, I think I'm just excited about all the changes happening in the tidyversity plier.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:28.000
That pattern of being able to read either the tabs of an excel spreadsheet or files that you would get from calling dir on a directory.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:35.000
And using that to be the starting point for a table, which then you use map to pull all the data in.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:40.000
Just allows you to naturally keep either file locations, names, and data all together.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
And then it flows naturally through the rest of the process.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:50.000
I literally just started using that a month or two ago and enjoy it quite a bit.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
I've used R for 15 years.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
I don't think ggplot2 was out.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
We had plier and reshape.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:09.000
I think that what can happen as you work, you get set in one way of doing things.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
And it's difficult to get off those patterns.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:18.000
So this pattern may be old to you guys, but to me it's been a great refresher to my work that I do.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:19.000
Great, thank you.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:21.000
Another question.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:26.000
What led you to the use of list columns instead of multiple tables at different levels?

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:30.000
Two thoughts.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:35.000
Attending RStudioConf and listening to Jenny Bryan talk about them with the Lego characters.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:41.000
But it's also just, to me, it just makes it easy to think about the data.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:46.000
Because if I need to get into the details, I can go get it.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
But very often I want to work at that summary level.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:55.000
And if something's spread across multiple tables, then to do that work, I might need to do joins just even for exploratory analysis.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:57.000
Nice.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:02.000
And you mentioned that you're working with FactSet data, and I assume other vendors.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
And when the format of that data changes, is that a challenge?

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:07.000
And how do you deal with that challenge?

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:18.000
Yeah, so I mentioned that this process that I laid out is robust typically to code errors, but not to data file formats changing.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:26.000
Example, depending on when you come in, FactSet will either have seven or eight rows in the header column.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:29.000
Or seven or eight rows in the header of a file.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:35.000
And so that used to kill, if that was hard-coded in a bunch of different areas in your code, that would kill the code.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:44.000
But now, like I said, taking that reading or processing code and separating into a single function, and then reusing that function.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.000
If it changes, I make the change once, and I can use it going forward.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:55.000
It's also something, obviously, that's obvious to have as a parameter in the function call.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:57.000
Okay.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:05.000
And have you considered, almost getting political, democratizing R across the firm outside of your immediate group?

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:11.000
And I think as an example, replacing Excel with usage by analysts.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:16.000
And if you have or have not, where's the friction you're seeing from that?

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:17.000
Sure.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:19.000
So Cognos is the first step there.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:27.000
When I got to Copper Rock, that quantitative model that we delivered every week as a 10,000-row spreadsheet was actually printed out.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:33.000
And people would print it front and back, open it, use rulers to scan and find it.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
So that was the level of user I was starting with.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:40.000
So to jump right into coding was not going to happen.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
But I think Cognos is the first step there.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:53.000
And then I've started more in meetings, because of the readability of dplyr code, actually dynamically answering questions with the code rather than saying, I'll get back to you.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:58.000
And I hope that as people see me do that, the code's up on the screen, they'll start to become more interested.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:01.000
Okay.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:05.000
There's a related question here about delivering data to non-R users in the org.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:08.000
Is Excel the only way that you're doing that, or are there other ways?

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:16.000
We do some via Microsoft Outlook emails, but it's very rudimentary.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
It's a flat text file, so it's not very...

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:25.000
I forget what the RStudio mailing package is, so I haven't used that.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:26.000
Blastula.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:27.000
Blastula.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:32.000
And, yeah, I think that's it.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:35.000
So it's Excel and it's Cognos.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:36.000
It's on 10 desktops.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:40.000
I mean, so it's roughly half of our firm, so it's a pretty good deployment.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.000
And we'll just do one more here from Frank.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:47.000
What was your workflow when designing the UI for the Shiny app?

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:51.000
How did you make sure the data was presented in a useful way to the bottoms-up panelists?

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:53.000
That's a good question.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:19:02.000
I think I tried it about three or four times, and I bounced back and forth between Flex Dashboard and Shiny or just standard Shiny.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:03.000
If you can see...

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:05.000
Oh, they've taken the slides off.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:17.000
I have two levels of tabs because there's a group of information that's related to stocks, information that's related to our portfolios, and each of those has tabs underneath it.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:22.000
And I had a hard time working in Flex Dashboard, so I went back and coded it from the beginning.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:26.000
But I use this tool in our morning meeting every day.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:27.000
It's up there.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
We bounce back and forth between Bloomberg and this tool.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:39.000
And so I certainly get a lot of live feedback with people who are having issues with it, or as I hear there's other data they'd like to see there, I incorporate that into the design.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:41.000
Thank you very much.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:43.000
Everybody please join me in thanking Shane.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:44.000
Thank you.

